            <h1>A GUIDE TO WEB TECH</h1>
            <p>The evolution of web technologies began in 1989 when <strong>Tim Berners-Lee</strong> created the World Wide Web, HTML, HTTP, and URLs, enabling the first interconnected websites. By 1993, <strong>Mosaic</strong> became the first widely used browser, followed by <strong>Netscape Navigator</strong> in 1994, which popularized web access.</p>
            <p>In 1995, <strong>JavaScript</strong> was developed by <strong>Brendan Eich</strong>, introducing interactivity to websites. That same year, <strong>Java</strong> allowed dynamic content with applets, and <strong>PHP</strong> (1995) and <strong>ASP</strong> (1996) enabled server-side scripting for dynamic content.</p>
            <p>The late 1990s saw <strong>CSS</strong> (Cascading Style Sheets) in 1996, which separated content from design, allowing for more flexible, visually appealing websites. As broadband internet became widespread in the 2000s, <strong>AJAX</strong> (2005) enabled faster, more responsive web applications by allowing data exchange without reloading pages.</p>
            <p>In the 2010s, <strong>HTML5</strong> and <strong>CSS3</strong> redefined multimedia and styling capabilities, and frameworks like <strong>React</strong>, <strong>Angular</strong>, and <strong>Vue.js</strong> revolutionized front-end development. Today, web technologies are highly interactive, supporting complex applications and mobile-friendly designs across a wide range of devices, setting the stage for continued innovation in the web's capabilities.</p>

            <h2>RESOURCES</h2>
